			<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; " >
												I don't really think they care about the experience gain of bards, as there are other classes that can gain exp in high-risk situtations as well.(See : Charm).  The DPS of a Charmed Hasted pet is pretty extreme too, and when you're taking into account AEing DPS you have to double the time just for time spent pulling.  And charm-fighting is not limited in the ways AEing is, it can work on summoners, indoor area's, small spaces, and any size mob-type.<br><br>I'm thinking the real issue here is the lag generated.  <br><br>So really it wouldn't be all that unreasonable to simply give a swarm-kiting style charm back to bards, as the mobs in a swarm are -FAR- less than that in an AE kite, generally around 4-7(Any more is pointless), as opposed to 10-20.<br><br>200 mana is pretty extreme for the new Charm, with a range that is litterally shorter than our AE songs range. It's almost like they're hitting us with a double-whammy here.  And Swarm-kiting is not reasonably scriptable, any more than the person who mentioned scripting 2 bards(who obviously thinks scripts are omnipotent and easy to create)<br><br>Frankly, this is -encouraging- macro exp'ing more than it is discouraging it.  What bard really wants to do nothing but chant-kite for solo exp?  Not only is it extremely uncomfortable on the wrists, it's very slow, as dull as can be, and still limited to mobs that do not summon.  Sure, any one of these isn't bad, but combine all 4 and yeah it's not really a viable exp'ing method, unless you happen to be able to do it while not at keyboard and a script just running it all day.  Then all of a sudden it's quite viable.  An AA every 3 hours is still 8 AA a day if you don't even have to be there.
																		
